shared_text:
Northeastern Nutrition
September 8 at 3:02 PM ¬∑

REMINDER: Free Breakfast & Lunch for ALL STUDENTS - through Dec.

Absolutely ALL STUDENTS can receive free lunch and breakfast through Dec. 31, 2020. You don't need to do anything (no applications, etc.). If/when your child goes through the lunch line, his/her order will simply come up as $0.00.

If you typically receive free or reduced lunch and you have not completed the application, please complete the application so that your child continues to receive this service throughout the rest of the school year (so it doesn't end in December). Free and reduced lunch count also impacts other programming, so we still want to have that count recorded accurately for the district.

Questions?

PLEASE SHARE: We are getting some questions about our school reopening plan after last night's Board meeting, so I wanted to send out a quick communication to keep our school family up to date:

- The first day of school for all students is Thursday, August 27, 2020.

- Families have the option of students attending school in person 5 days/week or enrolling in our fully on-line Bobcat Cyber Academy.

- If you would like to enroll your child in Bobcat Cyber Academy, please email Linda Miller at BobcatCyberAcademy@nebobcats.org.

-If you want your child to start in BCA on August 27, your enrollment request must be received by Thursday, August 20th.

School assignments and informational letters will be going out today! (We held them until last night's Board meeting in case anything changed - thank you for your patience!)

Have a wonderful rest of the day!

Dr. Stacey Sidle
Superintendent

PLEASE SHARE: The Safe and Healthy Community Initiative is proud to offer Stewards of Children at no cost to parents, educators, and community members.

Stewards of Children is a prevention training that teaches adults how to prevent, recognize, and react responsibly to child sexual abuse. The program is designed for organizations that serve youth and for individuals concerned about the safety of children. It is the only nationally distributed, evidence-informed program proven to increase knowledge, improve attitudes, and change child protective behaviors.

Additional information regarding the training can be found at the link below.

https://sites.google.com/view/yorkshci/home?utm_campaign=safecommunities&utm_source=facebook.com&utm_medium=cpm&fbclid=IwAR0mqcJPlzsG1WFbCFoCvMqhD6KP-_hIQkmWlFO9O_DSX4yc7A7cLfPnXpY

post_text: PLEASE SHARE: Rising senior Emily Froman was selected to attend the Academy Introduction Mission (AIM) program which takes place this summer at the United States Coast Guard Academy (USCGA). This program is exclusively available to students entering their senior year of high school. AIM is a one-week summer program where selected applicants interested in getting a taste of cadet life are immersed in the USCGA experience. AIM is considered to be the most realistic service academy summer orientation program. Having been selected from a highly competitive pool of exceptional applicants. Emily will work directly with Coast Guard officers, cadets, and faculty members who take great pride in having the opportunity to show prospective cadets what being a member of the Coast Guard is all about. AIM will help Emily discover whether the Academy experience is truly what she wants from college vs. a more traditional college route. This summer's AIM program will be held virtually due to COVID-19. Way to go Emily! #bobcatproudüêæ

We are proud to share the virtual ceremony for our Top 25 Awards. Each year, NHS recognizes the top 25 students in each class at an evening event for students and families. We also present our students with medals commemorating their achievements. Unfortunately, we were unable to host that in-person ceremony due to the COVID-19 pandemic and school closure. However, we believe it is still important to recognize our students and celebrate their accomplishments. Please enjoy this virtual ceremony where we recognize each of the top 25 students in each class by using the link below.

Seniors who are recognized were presented their medals when they received their caps and gowns earlier this year. Underclassmen will receive their medals when they return to school for the 2020-21 school year. Thank you to Mr. Iezzi, NHS asst. principal, for his work to put together this virtual ceremony. Congratulations to the recognized students and their families!

PLEASE SHARE: Due to a decrease in participation, TODAY will be our last grab & go meal distribution. We will be at the high school and York Haven from 10-11:30 am.

A HUGE thank you to all of the child nutrition staff who have been working tirelessly, some since our initial closure in March, to provide this service for our families.

We are working to secure some pop up food pick up dates and will continue to post that type of information here.

If your family is in need of assistance, please do not hesitate to reach out to our director, Kim Alessandroni at alessandronik@nebobcats.org.

post_text: Ryan Bridge, AKA Ryan the Bug Man, volunteered to host a virtual assembly on all things creepy and crawly. He is the father of Northeastern 5th grader, Owen Bridge. The assembly was all about the importance of bugs in the world. The message was they may be creepy and crawly, but they are not scary. He also had live bugs! The students and Mrs. Beagle really liked Kevin the Scorpion. His presentation was part of a series he offers to schools across the area, with a distance learning twist, so we could participate. Special thanks to Mr. Bridge. He really made our virtual field trip day very special!

post_text: CONGRATULATIONS! Mrs. Brenda Johnson was selected by The Pennsylvania-Delaware String Teachers Association to receive the Orchestra Director of the Year Award! One of her nominators stated, "Brenda is one of the hardest working orchestra directors I know. Both in the classroom and on the podium Brenda has high standards and the expectation is that the students will meet these standards, no exceptions. No rehearsal time is ever squandered. She forms strong personal relationships with her students, mentors them, and guides them through the turbulent waters of adolescence and college and post graduate processes." Nominees of this prestigious award must be currently teaching in a public or private school, or be directing a youth orchestra. The candidate must have demonstrated outstanding achievement as an orchestra teacher and conductor, resulting in major advancement of that candidate‚Äôs program with documentation of unusual success. Congratulations, Mrs. Johnson!

post_text: CONGRATULATIONS! The PMTA/DRIVE award is given yearly to a senior at Northeastern High School planning on entering the trucking, forklift or logistics field. Trevor Smith completed the Driving Resources and Innovation in Vehicular Education (DRIVE) class, which prepares students to obtain their CDL permit and driving skills to become a safe and competent driver. His skills on the CDL simulator were at the highest level of any student in the class, earning him a Gold Shifter (for mastery of double clutching, shift up, shift down and gear recovery) and Gold Mirrors (for backing skills). Trevor is currently working at APX York Sheet Metal and plans to get his CDL to assist his company in deliveries of their products. Congratulations to Trevor Smith earning this $500 award!

PLEASE SHARE: We understand that this is an unprecedented time for our entire community, filled with a lot of uncertainty. We also understand that the services these organizations provide have become even more essential to all of us. Our community is hurting and it's time for us to show that we've all got each other's backs.

In 2019, Give Local York made history by raising $3.2 MILLION for more than 300 nonprofits in our community.

Together, we can support causes across our community that will impact local kids and families, education, housing, and healthcare, our environment and economic development, the arts, history, culture and more. When we all give local, we make a huge impact. We may not be able to celebrate together, but that doesn't mean we don't have reason to celebrate!

https://www.givelocalyork.org/organizations/northeastern-foundation

We received some great news last week! Northeastern High School was again included in the US News and World Reports listing of the top high schools in America!

Some highlights-

‚òëÔ∏è NHS is ranked #5 in York, Adams, and Franklin Counties, #124 in PA and #3080 nationally.

‚òëÔ∏è There are over 700 high schools in PA and over 24,000 high schools in the US.

‚òëÔ∏è We want to thank and congratulate the entire school community for this recognition. We should all be proud of this achievement. NHS students continually impress us as they meet and exceed our expectations every day. We also thank all of our families who support our work with our students and finally, thank you to the amazing teachers at NHS who work so hard every day to ensure our students succeed! #BobcatProudüêæ

‚òëÔ∏è NHS is ranked #5 in York, Adams, and Franklin Counties, #124 in PA and #3080 nationally.

‚òëÔ∏è There are over 700 high schools in PA and over 24,000 high schools in the US.

‚òëÔ∏è We want to thank and congratulate the entire school community for this recognition. We should all be proud of this achievement. NHS students continually impress us as they meet and exceed our expectations every day. We also thank all of our families who support our work with our students and finally, thank you to the amazing teachers at NHS who work so hard every day to ensure our students succeed! #BobcatProudüêæ

USNEWS.COM
The Best High Schools in Pennsylvania, Ranked

post_text:
Being a new student isn't easy. Kianna Rivera moved to Northeastern with her family from Baltimore in late September. Kianna was welcomed to NMS by the Friends of Rachel (FOR) Club on her first day. A FOR leader on her team gave her a tour of the building and helped her find her classes, sat with
her at lunch, and answered her questions. On club days Kianna attended the FOR Club mentoring group organized by FOR leaders where new students have a chance to meet other new students and have fun playing games together. During this time Kianna also attended Lunch Bunch with FOR Club because finding a place to "fit in" a crowded middle school cafeteria can also be a bit challenging for a new student. Over the last 5 months it is hard to distinguish Kianna from the other FOR leaders she has bonded with in these sessions. In fact, she helps run the games and frequently volunteers her time helping new students during Club, in addition to mentoring herpeers in the Academic Mentoring Program (AMP). We are happy to welcome Kianna as our newest FOR leader. #BobcatProud

post_text: Third grade Orendorf students in Miss Keefer's class had a special guest visit their classroom this week. Officer Duncan took some time out of his busy work schedule to speak to the kids about his job as a police officer. Students learned that police officers are community helpers who keep people safe, come to the rescue when people are in trouble, and enforce the law. Officer Duncan showed these Bobcats some of the tools he needs to do his job well and students got to take home their own deputy police badge.

post_text: Mount Wolf Elementary students completed their 2nd No Place for Hate project of the school year for the AntiDefamation League. This project was called We Are All Welcome Here. It taught respect and empathy for others. Students were provided with an opportunity to realize the lesson of self acceptance and build a community of acceptance within our school. We challenged students to think critically by asking them to consider how the character in the book Chrysanthemum felt, and then relate those feelings to a similar experience they may have had regarding their own unique qualities and differences recognized in others.

post_text: Students at Orendorf Elementary had a great time dressing up as their favorite superheroes. These caped crusaders used the day to talk about what characteristics make up a great superhero. They discovered that many people with these same traits live in their community but just lack the cool costume. Students even practiced their writing skills by writing letters to their favorite super hero.
